76561198099004963,Not Recommended,237850,16588259,"Posted: 21 June, 2015",all,Miss Maverykk,"Let me first say that I am a huge fan of the first two games, the Longest Journey and the Longest Journey: Dreamfall. They are my favorite games of all time and I have played through them several times. If you expect this sequel to be anything like the first two, like I did, then you will be sorely disappointed.I played the Longest Journey and the Longest Journey: Dreamfall because of the compelling and interesting storyline, the gorgeous scenery and because I grew attached to the characters themselves. They are the type of games that let you escape into a dazzling and mysterious world with interesting characters that you can't get enough of.Dreamfall Chapters started out pretty well in the very beginning of Book 1, but as the game progressed it very quickly became obvious that the developers of the game wanted to shove their political views down your throat. The political agenda became very clear. For example, Zoë is engaged in a political campaign helping a socialist party, Zoë has a Marxist best friend and then every other girl in the street is walking around with hijab on.I did not buy this game to play ""Politics Simulator 2015"" or ""Baby Simulator"" (if you played this game you will know what I'm talking about).Dreamfall Chapters is otherwise visually gorgeous, but it lacks gameplay,story and puzzles. It also lacks clues to lead you to the next point.Let me also point out that the dialogue is a lot of times vulgar and forced. They manage to squeeze in profanity where it's not needed. Dropping the f-bomb and saying sh*t several times in a single sentence does not make good or ""cool"" dialogue. It seems like they are using profanity as filler to make up for a poor script. The Longest Journey and Dreamfall are not known for vulgar dialogue and it is not something that needed to be added.The developers have turned a fantastic game series into something bland and stereotypical with political propaganda. Zoë has become someone I don't recognize, doing and saying things that don't fit her personality as I know her from the Longest Journey: Dreamfall. I am also sad about April Ryan.I won't recommend this game to fans of the series, but I will likely continue with Book 3 because I invested time in the other chapters and want to see if there is some hope on the horizon. I doubt it though.I will replay the original games but not this one.Summary:+Visually gorgeous+Zoës updated model is beautiful (except her new haircut in book 3).-Blatant political agenda-Lacks story-Lacks gameplay-Lacks puzzles-Poor and forced dialogue-Vulgar language-Short chaptersTINY UPDATE 6/28-2015:Book 3 left my mouth agape. It was VERY short. I have no further comments as my opinion have not changed for the better.Thank you for reading."
,Not Recommended,237850,32589709,Posted: 20 June,all,Kye Plays Fair,"I'm not entirely sure why I finished this game. At first it was to either leave a fully considered negative review or give the game a chance to pull me in. However, it just kept going and going, and I believe it became an exercise in stubbornness with a small dash of curiosity.Short version: This game is a good idea brutally murdered by it's execution.If you want to hear why I think that, here's the long version.This game is more like a slightly interactive movie occasionally broken up with agonising treasure hunts attempting to masquerade as 'gameplay'. If ever you get stuck in this game, I would advise against grinding through the problem like I would any other game, and instead hit up a wiki. It's not worth the waste of time, chances are they didn't give you good directions or it's a case of crippling level design of the kind that places the object needed to complete a puzzle on the other side of the map near where you started from, once again causing you to go on a treasure hunt. The map of Europolis is nearly useless. The dialogue is painfully drawn out with excessive monologuing. Often, it will prevent you running or, worse still and maybe even more commonly, ground you in place, forcing you to listen to the lullaby of poorly conceived gameplay.This game certainly adapts to your choices wonderfully. The key ones at least. All the other ones brought me pain. I'm still not sure if it was physical or mental. I am all for the illusion of choice. I believe it to be a necessary evil in this type of game, hell, it's a fact of real life. I am rather forgiving of it done poorly too. Many of these choices went beyond poor, into the realm of looping me at one at certain points because I didn't do what it wanted me to.The animation was painful to watch. It was so jarringly horrid it actually made it as a major point in my list. The characters stand there, spouting this boring monologue, standing there motionless but for their mouths that move like gasping fish. There is no emotion displayed through either face or body language. No the minor movement of eyebrows that occurs once every few hours does not count. I came across a cat that zoomed past me on it's loop. It was moving fast, certainly, but nothing that would usually break immersion so harshly. The problem was that there was no bob in the cat's walk cycle. It was as if the cat hovered across the ground, legs working furiously to keep up with it's body. Although hilarious, it was another straw on a broken camel's back.Endless dialogue, poor game design, and shoddy coding has me truly confused as to how this game is reviewed as ""mostly positive""."
