76561198000016600,Not Recommended,237850,16737260,"Posted: 27 June, 2015",all,*****,"This game has great potential and I'd really want to like it, but it has many problems. The game is full of annoying puzzles, pointless erands, flat/unwitty dialogue and you don't really get anything good until after second half of episode three. To get this point, you need to suffer through roughly 10 hours of boringness. The last two episodes do have better storytelling and final episode does resolve the open issues from the original Dreamfall. Still, as a whole, the game is very mixed bag and I can't help but to feel unsatisfied after playing it.Problems (detailed list):1) Most of the puzzles are about finding right place to click and then clicking them in right order. Often you have good idea what you're supposed to do, but just can't find any way to do it. It's easy to miss interaction points and the game often hides them until you have completed all previous steps.2) Uninteresting characters, flat dialoque and everything is boring and monotone. I mean adventure games should be fun, witty or at least somehow exciting. This game just isn't. Last episodes are little bit better in this regard, but first episodes are just horrible.3) Filler content (lots of it). I can't help but to feel that some of the puzzles/tasks are there just strech the playing time. The episodic format is probably partly to blame. Each episode needs to be have decent length even if storywise the episode could be shorter.4) Uninteresting story. I kind of expected this game to pick up where the original Dreamfall left. Well... it doesn't. Original story isn't really resolved until in final episode (to lesser extent also in Episode 4). Instead we get boring relationship crap, boring rebels/magical stuff (which although has it's moments, we don't really care about) and other new stuff that is more or less irrelevant to bigger story.5) Character animations are just bad. Nothing quite ruins your character driven story like characters who look like they are some weird robots without any human emotion. I mean the original Dreamfall had better character animations frigging 10 years ago.6) Game is resource heavy (even after engine updates). I have two years old mid-price laptop, which runs similar 3D games pretty nicely. This game had parts which where barely playable."
,Not Recommended,237850,34840438,Posted: 9 September,all,🅟🅗🅐🅡🅐,"[SPOILER HEAVY RANT]As most people that have played this game, i come here as an old fan of the TLJ saga.While i don't own the other two entries on steam, i still own the original copies.Despite sitting in my backlog for an uncomfortably long time, i was still very excited to revisit the world of Stark and Arcadia. It was a well crafted world most of us had enjoyed years ago and i went in expecting the same old game i was so fond of.That was a mistake apparently.It's hard to dislike the game as it starts out great and agreed, it does start out incredibly fast paced but personally i found that to be fine. Most of the characters were established in previous entries. Fine for returning fans wanting direct continuation, probably immensely confusing for new players. My issues started halfway nearing the end. It becomes very clear that their choice of adopting this ""telltale-choice-related"" gameplay put serious strain on the writers. The game starts biting off more than it can chew with very disappointing consequences as a result. There's a ton in this game that simply goes nowhere.- ""Be careful, Dad. That's not Reza.""I remembered that line and it made me distrust him for obvious reasons. Even going so far as thinking the only reason they were together was because she was stuck in a simulation and was programmed to be in a relationship with him. (oh.) However, instead of uncovering this and having a plot twist where he could potentially be a Stark antagonist or have the option to save him? Nah, the character disappears halfway in the game only to show up in the epilogue like literally nothing has happened. Yes, he was a brainwashed sleeper agent but this was a plot point.. why? A red herring i suppose?- ""Zoe found the stickiest of the icky in her last couple of chapters and i found myself more weirded out than she was.""Going back to my impression of the writers being overwhelmed and having to.. actually finish the story in this final chapter, i felt this was glossed over so quickly. I get that she already went through a lot of weirdness so not a lot would phase her but learning you're a test-tube baby and getting double the confirmation on how much of a double whammy♥♥♥♥♥♥your mom actually is to only go ""oh, okay""..? The complete lack of emotion near the end (of a ton of characters, not just Zoe) just reaffirms they were rushing through things to get it over with.- ""Benrime""Multiple mentions of her throughout the game, would've been a small nostalgia nod to returning players. Jakai's sacrifice/betrayal was met with zero payoff, not even a small nod if she's okay in the epilogue for it. I'm simply going to assume she's okay.- ""Kian & Alayna""Ragnar says he always intended for Kian to be gay, i seriously find that hard to believe when he's made various comments about how hot the magical women look in Marcuria and the sexual tension between him and April in previous entries. Ultimately, even with Alayna shoehorned in as a physical gaydar, i don't give a♥♥♥♥♥♥about his sexual preference but i do have issues with how poorly it is delivered and how it contradicts established lore. I wonder what compelled them to even add this, i get that you get some brownie-points with the LGBT community for this but really, what did it even add to the narrative? Why didn't blind bob shout he was straight awkwardly? At least we get a boatride with what is probably the single worst delivery of the line ""I AM GAY"" ever. Couldn't we have skipped the boatride and seen some people getting rescued, Benrime perhaps?His sexual preference wasn't the only odd design choice for him. Early on in the game when arriving at the pub, he mentions he doesn't drink at all. later? he remarks that the beer is okay. Even later? He's comparing wines to the ones he's had back home. Which is it?- ""Saga/Lady Alvane/Deus Ex Machina""It was great to see the tie-in for this character, i could even argue her character as a standalone was actually pretty decent but her implementation into the story is horrendous. Little to no backstory. All we get is this shifter is ""special"" and her dad is extremely overprotective. Whatever plot point the game was trying to tie up or hurdle it was trying to overcome nearing the end, she was the answer. Why? ""muh prophecy."" I'll allude to it again, it came across like the writers needed to tie things up quick and what better way to do it than introducing a character that is (out of nowhere) near omniscient?quoted verbatim ""i feel like i'm playing life on cheat mode.""Another big shame regarding her character is how they gloss over what would've been vastly more interesting stories than the one they gave us regarding her. (Her learning about the prophecies. The war and her helping Kian become the bloodless king. All off-screen.)""I became amazing off-screen. Now go pick up my drawings."" I understand that in an ideal world, we would have gotten all of this in an extra game. My issue just lies purely with the poor implementation of it all. Beyond lazy and why i can not recommend this game.There's plenty more characters that are extremely underdeveloped for a story heavy game given the lackluster epilogue.Onor Hileriss (more like Hitleriss) getting nearly double the screentime as opposed to Hanna and Hope, Zoe's sisters and oncemore the lack of anything interesting regarding Saga and her offscreen action. At least we hear about Sully.I am fully aware i should be thanking the stars for even have gotten this game and in a weird way i am. Despite my rant and frustration with it i am grateful. I did enjoy playing but my god, the last chapter sours the entire experience.Such a shame because it frustrates me that i dislike the writing so much."
