,Not Recommended,237850,27727801,"Posted: 26 November, 2016",all,jkohen,"A boring game from cover to cover.Most of the time you spend in front of Dreamfall Chapters will be listening to hours and hours of exposition. This is delivered with animation that takes control away from you. The interactive sequences in between the exposition is what has to be one of the most boring professional adventure games of the XXI century. The first half of the game is plagued with aimless wandering in hard-to-navigate environments, and almost no puzzles; the second half fortunately dispenses with the backtracking, but the amount of puzzles remain slow. All the time the puzzles aren't connected to the story and are usually simple, tedious or both.My description might remind some of Telltales games, and they wouldn't be wrong to assume this game borrows inspiration from that company. I've enjoy most Telltales' games, because they excel at pacing and engagement. The decisions feel real, while in Dreamfall Chapters they feel random and unimportant (what food should I buy Reza?!)This is all a shame, because Dreamfall Chapters' art is beautiful and the designers had total dedication to the details. The world feels alive and comes through believable. The pacing however ruined it for me. For instance, after the game's climax the player is treated to, I kid not, 20 minutes of exposition in the form of epilogues. Most big characters get at least one epilogue. The major characters' epilogues get their own epilogues. One character that doesn't have a main role until the end of the last part has 3 or 4 epilogues (I lost count). At this point the player's interest is gone, and yet the writers decided to self-indulge into more exposition, most of which is a retelling of the game's events without adding any critical information.I played this game despite the negative reviews because some reviewers claimed it gets better on the second half. While it does get better in my opinion, it never gets good, and all the flaws except backtracking are carried over."
