76561198001938023,Not Recommended,237850,28461142,"Posted: 18 December, 2016",all,mb_williams,"For an original TLJ fan, this game is a disappointment. Briefly, it is an adventure game where you don't go anywhere.Rather than do what made TLJ interesting - create settings and characters - Ragnar Tornquist has gone on a nostalgia trip. TLJ was essentially an interactive stage play. Each scene had a backdrop, and a few props in front of it, and the characters. Since the graphics for each location were simple, the studio could afford to make lots of them, and the journey could unfold.In this game, Tornquist spent the budget recreating locations in Arcadia and Stark - many of which have already been seen - in full 3D. This means that until very late in the game, most of the action happens in one hub in each world. To speak of the ""hub"" in Stark is an exaggeration, because Zoe never exactly travels anywhere else. People talk mysteriously behind her back, friends come and go, but none of it ever really matters. So there's half a story missing already.Things are somewhat better on the Arcadia side, but still ... not much novelty, just moving the old game pieces around with the occasional ""I am your father"" twist.The choice element is a gimmick that begs you to replay a game that didn't deliver the first time around, and won't the second time either."
