76561198115341169,Recommended,237850,23624478,"Posted: 17 June, 2016",all,cllewis10,"One of the most compelling and incredible games I've ever played. The graphics are amazing--I found myself enjoying just wandering around Propast. Each scene is ginormous and detailed. Having watched Marcuria develop from the first TLJ and Dreamfall: TLJ, I must say they've perfected it's design in Chapters. It was the perfect little fairytale town. The story takes it's time unfolding, and that's fine. You don't want to get in a hurry to finish, because then you have to find something else to do. And there is NO combat or stealth gameplay, much to my relief. Glad the developers decided to kill that idea after the disastrous Dreamfall: TLJ.Take heed: Anyone who tells you that you don't need to play The Longest Journey or the sequel Dreamfall: The Longest Journey is fully and completely LYING to you. If you are playing Chapters and haven't played the other two, stop what you're doing now and go back to the beginning of the trilogy. These are an absolute must if you want to fully understand and appreciate what's going on and pick up on the nuances.A word of warning, the task of completing the first two games in the trilogy is a bit of a drag (just my opinion). The storylines are fantastic, but it's the gameplay that will make you go grrr. The first one, The Longest Journey, was released in 1999 and the graphics, well...they were cutting edge for the turn of the century, but having played it for the first time in 2016, I was woefully underwhelmed. The storyline is fantastic, though, and you'll find you can easily overlook the ancient technology. And then the second one, Dreamfall TLJ, well...while the storyline of the second one is just as rich and deep as the rest of them, it contains elements of combat and stealth (hiding from beasties and what-nots) that I did not care for AT ALL. I'm a purist when it comes to adventure games. I like to relax and appreciate the environment and storyline--if I wanted action I would go play an arcade game. I don't know how the developers slept at night after giving us the frustrating combat/stealth garbage that went with Dreamfall. Even people who enjoy that kind of thing found it bad, sluggish, and just overall poorly designed. One good thing (and the only good thing) about it is there's an autosave feature just before a fight, and you don't run out of lives so you can die as many times as it takes to get it, and you will, eventually. If I could do it, you most certainly can. But anyway, like I said, in order to appreciate Chapters, you gotta get through the first two games. So I recommend you get an XBox 360 controller for Windows (about $20 if you want brand new), because that's the only way you're going to get through Dreamfall:TLJ without tearing your hair out.Enjoy your trip down the rabbit hole, and don't forget to come up for air."
76561197995287477,Recommended,237850,28278266,"Posted: 9 December, 2016",all,Juliaana,"A very likeable story rich adventure game. I recommend first playing the first part of the series, ""The Longest Journey"" (if you can bear it) and even more so the second part ""Dreamfall: The Longest Journey"" which provides a lot of background and introduces the main characters.The combat system of the previous game of the series (Dreamfall:TLJ) has fortunately been removed and Chapters has been made a choice-based game. The choices obviously dont affect the grand story arc but are still interesting and meaningful. You mainly play as Zoe and Kian as in the previous game, and now and then the new character Saga at various ages (starting at toddler age and later at age 4 which is very cute).If you come from Dreamfall:TLJ, note that the voice actors for both Zoe and Kian unfortunately changed. At first this is very noticeable especially for Zoe but Charlotte Ritchie does a very good job and it's easily forgotten after a short while.Some adventure games these days have poorly constructed/underbudget/strange/too short/outright sad endings but Dreamfall isn't one of them. The ending is well proportioned and bearable for soft hearts like me."
