,Not Recommended,237850,31537370,Posted: 4 May,all,Pang Tong,"A decent conclusion to the ""The Longest Journey"" saga, although I think the Dreamfall games made the whole series more complicated than was necessary. The game takes itself quite seriously and feels like it's trying to be Game of Thrones sometimes with overtly ""edgy"" themes, but it falls flat because the plot doesn't actually explore any of the issues it brings up. The Azadi are almost literally just the Nazis.There's lots of dialogue which is nice sometimes but overall it's quite poorly paced so you'll probably end up getting sick of it and skipping through the voice acting. The characters feel mostly fake and are written more like quirky sitcom characters than real people.There's not much to the gameplay or puzzles, which mostly revolve around running around a large open area to find the one object or character you're allowed to interact with. Although this helps prevent the game suffering from ""adventure game logic syndrome"" where solutions to puzzles don't make sense, it means there's actually not much gameplay at all and the game feels more like a visual novel than a puzzle adventure like the original The Longest Journey.The game is obsessed with offering choice, going so far as to regularly remind you when a choice you made is having an impact on the story, and even recapping how important your choices were at the end of each episode. The choices do actually make a bit more of an impact on the story than say, Telltale products, but ultimately the story plays out in much the same way regardless, so the extreme focus on your choices feels hollow and ingratiating.My advice is: play The Longest Journey, but skip Dreamfall: TLJ and Dreamfall: Chapters. Chapters is only worth it to see the conclusion to the numerous dangling plot threads that Dreamfall: TLJ left on its cliffhanger ending."
