76561198020361304,Recommended,237850,24031981,"Posted: 2 July, 2016",all,SinusPi,"* No-spoilers review: *The game's Books One through Four are nothing if not spectacular and spin the story's threads in a very skilled and logical and thought-provoking manner. I couldn't recommend them more.And then comes Book Five. Which I can only describe as: WTF?First of all, it's not a Book like the others, it's an overblown ending sequence, with very brief interactive intermissions. It's so obviously rushed, that I immediately catch myself excusing the creators for some simple reason - I don't know, running out of money? out of studio time? personal issues? - the likes of which tend to plague Kickstarter-born, drawn-out projects - and I start thinking, ""well, all right, it was probably either a rushed Book Five or no Book Five"". But then again I slap myself mentally a little. After all, I did pay for five books of an interactive story. and instead I got four interactive books and one blatantly rushed epilogue. Mixed feelings abound.Oh, and if it were a nice, wrapping-it-all, climactic epilogue, I may not have whined as I am. But whine I shall.* Spoilers from here on. *First of all... Saga. Previously a doodling toddler, known to have some connection to April. A reincarnation? A kindred soul? Aaactually, no, rather a rebellious songliner (what?) who prefers songs to drawings now (because?) and she's actually traveled a countless myriad worlds, that's what she does, playing life on cheat mode and apparently being a professional prophecy-fulfiller. WHAT? Oh never mind, we'll never know. And who is this Rose, whom old Saga mentions when talking about flying teacups and dragonflies, wasn't it Queenie the Chinese-ish old lady who did those? Mind you, I love throwaway expositions and  cliffhanger endings, but not instead of a proper, logical, consistent wrap-up.Then... Kian's future. Saga steps in, saves the day, actually saves several decades, making Kian the Bloodless King with herself by his side. Roll credits, ""And The Adventure Continues""! Aaactually, no, we're seeing Kian as the king, and then Saga as an old crone, and worlds after the Merge, and... Wait, wait, the time to do a cute, perversely counter-climactic cliffhanger is over, why do we have SEVERAL of them?Next... Undreaming takes center stage. It's the most horrible, destructive force! Let's set it free. Book Four mentioned the Nightmare as being the necessary, unavoidable dark side of the Dreaming, very specifically NOT the same as Undreaming, which just cancels out everything. And yet here we go, Undreaming has an Undreamer and is needed to Balance? What?And next... The Machine. On the Arcadia side, it was built by Westhouse to power the spear to unleash the Undreaming, all right, but how come a very similar machine was built on the Stark side at the same time? Sure, there's a nice ""worlds mirrored"" vibe here, but it's never explained nor even hinted at. Brian only names Helena a ""tool"", hardly a mere insult, rather a direct reference to her being a pawn in his game - but wasn't he, like, unable to get to Stark in any way, let alone manipulate people there? Also, does Eingana ""collect dream energy"" (for whatever purpose and whatever that is), or ""influence people's dreams to reshape reality""? Those are two very different concepts, and yet they're mixed up in the same dialogue.Finally... It was all about choices so far. We got to decide people's lives or deaths, we got to watch the Balance icon shift this way or another... And in the end, Zoe simply calls Helena ""insane"" and prefers to help destroy Eingana, without a single thought that maybe, just maybe, ""rebooting the world, without disease, without violence"" might actually be a GOOD thing, if possible? No moral dilemmas, no free will versus wise control?All this looks as if the storywriter for the previous four Books got fired, and a new one was brought in for the last Book, and he/she did as good a job as they could after being given only 10 minutes to acquaint themselves with the whole story so far.Book Five belongs in a different game, in a different reality. A damn shame. The first four Books are truly magical, enthralling and a true pleasure to play - but Book Five just deserves a rewrite."
