,Recommended,237850,28696988,"Posted: 26 December, 2016",all,Z o,"If you're a fan of story driven games, this one is wonderful.But it's not perfect.  In fact there's a lot that I would want to improve about it - better puzzles and more freedom to find solutions to them, for instance.  Some of the puzzles were a bit frustrating to figure out the solutions to, and it wasn't like they were hard and then very satisfying to solve: they were just frustrating.  For instance (and this isn't necessarily the best or only example, it's just the one that comes to mind) during one of the missions you have to figure out a way to distract a guard.  You can think of a million different ways to do it, but sadly the game is limiting to the degree that there's only one solution that is written into the game, and it's not even necessarily the most obvious one.However, the characters, settings, and stories that make up Dreamfall Chapters are really cool.  And so is the soundtrack.  I found myself inspired by many of the themes and story elements in this game (for instance, in the scientific half of the Twin Worlds of Dreamfall, Stark, many of the inhabitants of the city Europolis are ""dream junkies."" The junkies wear ""dream machines"" and essentially jack in and check out, finding better lives for themselves inside of their dreams - you can see how that kind of thing poses some philosophical questions!).I'll openly admit some bias, as I really enjoyed playing Dreamfall: The Longest Journey on X-Box now over a decade ago.  So I bought Chapters upon its release, and have been playing each ""book"" as they came out.  I won't say this game is one that really digs its claws in and demands to be finished right away.  It took me more than a year to finish it, and that's not _only_ because of the way the game was released.  But the story is interesting, and there's enough to chew on, that it's a satisfying play and you'll remember what's going on every time you pick it back up.This game won't be right for everyone.  It's not action packed, there's no precision timing or jumping or aiming, and there's no combat.  But strip away some of the frustrating mechanics of how the game works and there's a beautiful and sincere story being told with a very rich cast of characters."
