,Recommended,237850,12623537,"Posted: 25 October, 2014",all,32MegaPowah,"I'll say this right now. If you haven't played the previous two gamesThe Longest JourneyorDreamfallplease go out and play them, even if you only playDreamfall. This game references them heavily, requiring the player to have some prerequisite knowledge in order to put events in the game into context. Thankfully it doesn't sacrifice the pace of the story in lieu of accessibility.It's a recurring theme actually. In a choice between story and something else, this game chooses the former. Every single time. You'll need to set your own expectations, if you come into this expecting something akin to a fantastic interactive story with some extremely well realised characters, you will not be disappointed. If you're the type of person that gets bored with dialogue and skips cutscenes to carry on playing then refrain from purchasing it.Like Myst, Gone Home, and The Walking Dead, this is an experience that requires you to take a back seat, and just enjoy the narrative presented. After seeing a presentation from Red Thread a year or two back, I was worried that the new choice system would be a cliched binary ""save the puppy"" or ""eat the puppy alive"" moral dichotomy, and that it would compromise the main characters' intended personalities. Thankfully that isn't the case. Choices never fall outside their conceivable paths of action, but there are clear distinctions between them. Neither do a lot of them centre on a moral choice, instead them being a personal one.Art direction is as fantastic as ever, and they really manage to drive home the wider state of the world, particularly in Europolis. Last time around it was Arcadia that blew me away so it's a nice change. There are some flaws in execution, such as weirdly skinned characers, art assets that can be a little rough, and some minor shader issues. But if you a consider it a tradeoff to prevent a situation as in Dragon Age 2 where areas and assets were just constantly re-used I'd happily take it.I do have issues with framerate in some parts, but since I haven't updated my drivers in ever I'll refrain from making a judgement on it just yet.tl;dr: If you played and like the previous two, it offers everything they did and more. You won't be disappointed with it. If you're new to the franchise purchase and play the previous one first, if not both. If you like them buy this one. If you hate games with cutscenes and dialogue, only wanting to get to the next level, then stay away like the plague."
76561198102143738,Recommended,237850,12782892,"Posted: 3 November, 2014",all,Jarithom,"I really enjoyed this game and such a refreshing change from the blood and gore and violence of so many games today. This is a game I can share with my kids. We have played all the previous Dreamfall games and have been waiting impatiently for this one. What I like about it: the atmosphere of Propast is extremely well done and it was fascinating to just explore. I like that you can make choices that affect the way the game unfolds although it is not clear in what way it affects the game as yet. Kudos to the developers for doing some radical things including role-playing Saga, a toddler! It was so cute to listen to her babbling and giggling as I explored the house and tried to dodge Dad to get to the shiny sparkly thing!  The characters are not stereotypes, there is no gratuitous cleavage, what a change that is!  What I don't like about it: there is not much to get one's teeth into yet but hopefully that will come. Also the people of Propast: no kids (except one), very few old people, no fat people, body types are the same (i.e. ""ideal"") (great that there is a lot of ethnic diversity though). But the main problem for me is that I have to wait for the next chapter!!!!!"
,Recommended,237850,12728163,"Posted: 1 November, 2014",all,TheManko,"Dreamfall Chapters is now over, and as a fan of this series I'm a bit split over what to think. The game not only follows up on the end of Dreamfall, it also ties together its story with The Longest Journey to make this a trilogy, and not a series of standalone games. The story ends up being so big, with so many pieces moving at once, that it'll take some time after to sort out just what happened in the end.It's palpable just how strained for resources the development team of Dreamfall Chapters was. They do the best they can, but you often sense how shortcuts were made to avoid animating characters as much as possible. The character animations were always a weakness of this series, so at this point it's tradition for it to be the weakest aspect. Thankfully, the traditional strengths of the series are still here, with music being very good, and the overall art direction and rendering being almost good enough to make up for the animation. But it's also clear how this is a lower budget title than the original Dreamfall, as it holds up remarkably well in comparison to this.What also makes the creaky production values evident is how ambitious the game is. There's multiple branching paths through the game, leading to a myriad of different endings. How this plays out is unfortunate, as the scenes don't flow together particularly well. The seams between the alternative scenes is sharp, as the game fades out and loads between each scene. So while it was exciting in the moment to make a choice, as you couldn't predict the outcome, it came at a cost of a fractured ending.As for the content of the ending, I'm not sure how I feel yet. Some of the scenes were good, others were a bit too obvious, without the resonance and power you'd hope for in an ending, owing to how it felt like a part of separate scenes shown to you like interchangeable blocks. Some of the mysteries are revealed in ways that don't live up to how powerful they were while they were unsolved. One of the great strengths of the series has been how the mysterious otherworldly realm of dreams and magic evoke a genuine sense of wonder. Having it be explained reduced its power. At the same time, some parts of the story I wanted answers to remain unexplained, creating a double whammy of disappointment in learning the truth, and frustration at not knowing more.Despite all this, I'm still positive about Dreamfall Chapters as a whole. It consistently created scenes that were exciting on multiple levels. It wasn't afraid to put political themes in its storyline, and have the story be about them,♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥off parts of the fanbase in the process. It's a bit messy, with some character relations not clicking with me, and many jokes falling flat. But I could look past those things, as it was still charming enough to work. I can be unforgiving of flaws in slick big budget productions. But in this game, where it feels like a miracle anything ended up on screen at all, I can look past the execution and see what they were going for. This is a million times more ambitious, and tries to say a thousand more things than most games do. I appreciate the effort.The audience for Dreamfall Chapters is narrow. It demands you've played The Longest Journey and Dreamfall to completion. This isn't the entry point for the series. But as an ending, it's good enough. It has loads of problems, but I'm certain the majority of people who play this after the first two games will be happy with it. It's been a long time coming, but I'm glad it finally got an ending, even if I would've wanted it to be better. But under the circumstances, it couldn't be better."
