76561198040780621,Recommended,237850,26186741,"Posted: 23 October, 2016",all,Ash,"I found out about Dreamfall after hearing about the successful Kickstarter of this game. After completing it I wish I had been there to back it. Dreamfall TLJ was an excellent story-driven game, and Chapters continues that. The game switches between the two main characters: Zoe and Kian. At times their stories intertwine with each other. Which brings me to the writing. Without spoiling anything, the plot is filled with ups and downs and makes you feel invested and immersed. And as with many good RPGs there are plenty of moments that will make you laugh, perhaps even cry. As far as mechanics go it is far smoother than either of the previous games in the series which comes with it being built in a more modern engine. This is helped by the removal of direct combat. Something that I felt was particularly stiff and frustrating in the previous game and didn't quite belong.If I had to say anything bad it would be that the game came out in five books. I get the developer what the Red Thread Games was trying to do and I appreciate getting to play the game earlier, but by the time I finished book five I was a bit fuzzy on some of the details from the earlier books. If you are buying this game today this doesn't matter. Another thing to be aware of that can stump people at times is that you have to be sure to look all around you, 360 degrees, every nook and cranny. Sometimes things that aren't meant to be puzzles end up holding people up, myself and LPers included.All in all a fantastic game! Highly recommend, but you should probably play Dreamfall: The Longest Journey first."
