,Recommended,237850,28459538,"Posted: 18 December, 2016",all,PookPunk,"Do I recommend Dreamfall Chapters? Yes, but only if you played the previous 2006 Dreamfall game and 1999’s The Longest Journey. Is it an improvement over the previous Dreamfall game? Yes. Chapters fixes the flawed gameplay of the previous installment by removing combat and stealth modes. Thus, Chapters is designed to be a bit more linear, but it still has that open world feel. It feels more like an adventure game and less like an action/adventure (like the original DF). Also, Chapters introduces a new choice system, which can affect different outcomes in the story. Overall, Chapters concludes the events from the previous installment (and even TLJ to an extent). The game is beautifully rendered and sounds great. Ragnar Tørnquist knows how to tell an engaging story. If you enjoyed the other two games you owe it to yourself to play Chapters.Here's the bad. The first couple Books are slow. Things kick up a bit around Book 3 and onwards. Also, running around everywhere can get repetitive. I’ll get straight to the point and clarify that the DF entries are inferior to the original game (TLJ). First, the DF games exclude the adventure genre elements of TLJ such as: the 2D prerendered backdrops, the wacky puzzles, and the classic point-n-click interface. Also, Zoe Castillo steals the spotlight from April Ryan. However, April is still essentially the primary focus in the DF games despite serving as a supporting character. The only thing that saves the DF games is the return of the engrossing worlds and characters Tørnquist introduced in TLJ. Otherwise, the DF games can be deemed as unnecessary as TLJ stands quite well on its own.Finally, Chapters concludes the previous installment quite well. If the true sequel to TLJ (aka TLJ Home) is ever greenlit it's essential to have April Ryan as the protagonist and return to the roots of the original. There is a big story gap between TLJ and DF that has not been told, which might serve as that true sequel fans have wanted. If Tørnquist, Red Thread Games, or Funcom can’t make this happen then I see no point in continuing from Chapters. Just play the game and you’ll see what I mean. In the meantime, the original TLJ really stands on its own and is a PC classic. If you’ve never played it, I highly recommend playing it over or prior to the Dreamfall spin-offs."
