,Recommended,237850,20831148,"Posted: 29 January, 2016",all,queen_of_leander,"Book 5, can't hardly wait. Problem is, since there is no way to start a new save with my current data still in tact, this does somewhat pose a dilemma for me, especially since I want to go back and pick some different options. If book 5 happens to come out in a few months, well it would be nice if I can keep the info I have now. Not that getting back there would be too difficult (but it is time consuming). This game is excellent. The story is very emotive, very smart, it really does feel like your decisions have weight. I felt like it was such a weighty cliff hanger at the end of this game, very bittersweet, sad but hopeful. As a person who was not familiar with the previous games, I sort of just jumped in, based on some videos about it and other reviews. I have to say, I was not disappointed. Sometimes, there were parts, especially during book 1 & 2 where I had to think about things on some puzzles, or how to interact with an item or how I was suppose to use said item, but it's not impossible things. The vents was very tricky and I admit, I had to seek out help during that part, but I did not want to read hints on other parts of the game. I really did want to be surprised by the results. I came to the conclusion that there are a few choices which are better than others, but like most things, there's really no wrong answer. Life by its nature is reactive, it's fluid, it's changing, and this game does a great job of capturing how tough it is to know which is the right path, and is there truly a right path, rather than simply things you get caught up in sometimes? I like how this game truly makes you think about things, it's not the average cookie-cutter adventure/RPG, but it's not morbid, it's strange I'll give you that, but in a wonderful way really.I do think this game would be better served by allowing you to save different formats, instead of it rewriting over your saves. I don't honestly know why some games choose to do that, but that is always a little annoying for those of us who need to see different sides of a game, who want to get different perspectives (and perspective, isn't that mostly what life is about anyway?). But, it's still probably a minor point. I have to say that, I would have prefered some of the buildings to be a tad more interactive, just being able to go inside more places instead of only being allowed in certain areas, but I realize this was fan-backed, so I have to say in that respect, much was accomplished from that and the development team seemed to make good use of what was provided. It's a game I'm proud to say I wanted to finish, and I'm still thinking about Saga, and Zoe.I really thought that showing Saga grow from a baby to a child to a teen was really clever, it gave me a strange sense of ...wonder I guess, development did a really good job of making that baby look so very realistic, baby fat and chubby cheeks, and I loved that locket, it was so touching to see that scene, and I really felt for Saga's dad (even if he placed those wards in the first place, I'm sure he had his reasons, even if they were misguided). I loved how authenic Saga's dad's accent was, I swear he was from Dublin, who knows maybe that voice actor was haha.And correct me if I'm wrong, but didn't Stephanie Leonidas play Zoe? I only know because I've seen mirror mask like 20 times, so you get to pick up things when you hear someone enough, anyway, it does sound like her, but not fully sure if it is. In fact, so many of the voice actors sound really authenicly UKish, you even threw in some Cockney sounding rustic gents, in the Mercuria village, like some of the farmers saying ""I'm really lookin' forward to this years fes-teee-val, I could really hear that rustic charm, it really made me laugh. I'm from America, though I have a few UK friends, but I've never been to any of the isles, but you get to know a thing or two about voices once you've heard an accent enough. Like how the people from London tend to say ""innit"", the cockney people tend to put extra S's on everything and they generally reflect a more laid back way, like people in the south in American do, though we tend to not say ""we be over there"", now we might say reckon, which is strange the similarities there.Anyway, sorry...nerd alert I like language and and literature. Anyway, I've played alot of games where the voice acting just did not sound believable, but it's really awesome in this game, closest one was perhaps Bard's Tale (but then again Cary Elwes is Welsh I believe, kind of surprised I didn't hear his voice in this, wouldn't he have also made a great Doctor therapist, wink, wink). I do like how there's different sounding nationalities, and all the languages seem hodge-podge, like some of the curses are mashed together, you saw this in Blade Runner (movie/short story), though there were quite a few Indian sounding people as well, but it really gave the future a more wider scope. Isn't it ironic in the story though, that everyone doesn't seem to make a big deal about langauge or race, in the future, it's when Kian is in his world, where people start discriminating against magicals (book 4, especially the end, reminded me of the Nazi concentration camps, to be honest... Ge'en was very believable, and I did not expect the admin of the camp to look like that, very unassuming, but isn't that how it is sometimes? Scary.I'm hoping in book 5 we'll find out what happened to Bip, he became very endearing, I almost felt bad about not telling him the truth about his parents, even though I know the game is usually ran a certain way, if I think about it psychologically, he needed to prepare himself for that death camp; it might have helped him to put up a smarter fight, though in the end he's still a boy, not superman. I really felt for his character, and I really didn't feel guilty about knowing that woman into the pit, it was quite enjoyable really, she was really sadistic, and the joke between Kian and Leiko was funny, though it makes me wonder, if you go solo ...I do wonder, does she just point the gun at Kian, and if so how would you distract her? That's part of the joy to getting more than one perspective in a game. I'll really enjoy another play through, but I'm not sure if I should wait, and maybe part 5 will come out in a few months, if that's the case I can probably wait then, but I would like to alter a few of my decisions on a next run through, since I'm fairly aware which choices are the worse ones. There are a few parts where it's simply personal choice, like about either torturing that solider or not doing it, in one instance Enu will like you, in another Leiko will dislike you (but you can redeem with him later). In this respect, it is in a similar vain as many of the Tell-tale games, however...I'll choice fantasy and sci-fi anyday over zombie/horror, perhaps because I'm more a dream than a realist, but people can display many sides sometimes, just depends on which you do/enjoy the most? I really recommend this game, especially to a buff of either genre, and I do enjoy my share of thriller titles, but I'd rather be thought-provoked, than just adrenalined all the time, I will admit Yaga's house was scary as hell though, and that really creepy feeling you get when you hear that voice (yikes), but it was only in one part of the game, so it's not like my adrenaline was high the whole time. I sort of like that, when it's used as a rare effect, but not in everything. I mean, once you get jump scared 20 times it sort of looses it's rush, and you're still getting anxiety which is not so good on the stress meter you know. A good story can win over game play, but it all matters. This game felt like just the right balace to make it immersive, in fact when you first see the sprawling city, it's easy to just be in wonder at the sheer size of it, it really felt like another world."
