,Recommended,237850,20905474,"Posted: 1 February, 2016",all,Gaffit,"I originally bought this game as a long time fan of both The Longest Journey series and Ragnar Tornquist's work. And I have to admit, at first I was a bit underwhelmed. It was great seeing how all the characters were holding up after all these years. But in the first Book it seemed like the team was just getting used to the Unity Engine. The scene locations are all gorgeus and packed with details and the character models all look good, but the first book involved a lot of running back and forth. But after sticking with it through the first book, the game really picks up. The plot kicks off, and actions have the most ridiculous consequences. I'm refusing to take any alternative choices at the moment so I can keep my ""canon"" run, but I can see how by making a few different choices, you could be playing a completely different game.The characters are all charming and humor is spot on. The sad moments leave me feeling dwelling on my mistakes all day and triumphant moments make me feel happy that I just got everyone through. I'd highly recommend this game to any and all TLJ fans, it's an instant buy. But for new players, I'd recommend going back and playing the first two games to really get the most out of the experience. They do include a nice ""The Story So Far"" movie in the game, but by playing the first two games you get a much better feel for the story, characters, and world of the longest journey."
