,Recommended,237850,20417548,"Posted: 9 January, 2016",all,JeiFaeKlubs,"Years ago, I played Dreamfall: The longest Journey on a ♥♥♥♥♥♥ PC without much experience with PC games, and loved it, even though I barely remember the story. So I had to buy this game for nostalgia reasons. Again, I love it.The story and the really well developt characters alone makes it worthwhile and fun. The puzzles are good, there's even some tiny form of stealth in there. I expected some sort of combat like in ""The Longest Journey"", but even without that it is really fun to play.I really liked the choices, too, so far. Not all choices have big influences on the story, and because I've seen with a lot of these ""your choices matter""-games, I don't expect the ending to be completely different and influenced by everything you decided. But the NPCs give you the feeling the choices matter. Mostly it's relationships that depend on what you do, and seemingly also some lives. Also, not every choice is obvious and you'll only notice later that you actually made that choice, which is a great touch. And sometimes your choices don't matter at all, just like in real life :)I have some negative points, but those shouldn't keep you from playing this game:* The first two hours or so in the first book start off a bit slow. You run around a lot, you talk a lot, you don't really get to do that much. From a story-perspective, it makes sense, but it's very linear.* It is sometimes buggy, though I know the devs are working on it. Most bugs I've encountered fixed themselves after restarting the game.* The puzzles are linear. I would have loved to have two or three different possibilities to approach most puzzles. the levels are also quite linear, there's not much exploring to be done - which I would have loved to see in such a rich and well-developed world as this.EDIT: Oh yes, and there's a lot of swearing and genital-jokes in there! Fits the settings perfectly ;)"
