,Not Recommended,237850,23730344,"Posted: 23 June, 2016",all,Shirish,"TL;DR : The story of Dreamfall: The Longest Journey and Dreamfall Chapters, while set in the same universe as The Longest Journey and with common characters, feels very unrelated to the story of TLJ. If you liked the second game's story and are okay with the first game being left as a side-show, then you'll probably love Dreamfall Chapters. If not, you'll likely be left with a bitter taste in the mouth.-------------------------------------Like most of the people who purchased this game, I absolutely love The Longest Journey and can sing its praises all day. The main reason why I didn't like Dreamfall Chapters is that it overcomplicates the storyline of the first two games, and in the process, does not properly close out the entire saga.One of the great things about The Longest Journey was that the protagonist, April Ryan, was very much likeable. Her adventures and the settings/locations of her adventures inspired a sense of wonder (remember seeing Marcuria for the first time?). The second game, Dreamfall, continued along the same lines but the focus of the story started shifting from maintaining a balance between the two worlds to dreaming/undreaming, etc.And now for Dreamfall Chapters: the storyline is carried in such a different direction that it seems almost completely unrelated to the first game. It's as if they forgot about The Longest Journey and only provided a continuation of Dreamfall (the second game).None of the characters, including April Ryan, are given a proper or satisfactory closure.This includes Abnaxus, the Draic Kin, etc. There is almost no mention of what the hell happened to any of those characters after the end of the first game. I won't say any more about this because I don't want to spoil anything, but out of the 25 hours that I played, not more than 20 or 30 minutes were dedicated to the original TLJ characters except Crow. The mess-up with the story could've been offset if there were good puzzles, but aside from a couple of tricky ones in the first 3 chapters, the rest are absolute no-brainers. Book 5 has no puzzles at all- it's more or less an interactive movie where you click on dialog choices or search for stuff.To sum up, if you didn't like or care about the first game but liked the Dreamfall storyline, it's worth playing. But if you want a proper closure to The Longest Journey saga that started in 1999, you will most definitely be disappointed. For me, it begins with and ends at the first game itself."
