,Not Recommended,237850,26309490,"Posted: 30 October, 2016",all,goc9000,"Alas, all the polish and work that went into the game is for naught as it is still a disappointment both by modern standards as well as in comparison with the original The Longest Journey.One of the biggest problems is that the political aspects are far too strident in this installment. While in earlier games you could see signs of the writers' political bent, it was still subtle enough, and integrated into the plot in such a manner that it was possible for people of nearly all political beliefs to enjoy the game to the full. With Chapters, it's difficult not to imagine the writing team as consisting exclusively of radical leftist progressives with neither the ability nor the desire to portray their opponents' arguments in a fair light. In both Stark and Arcadia, you are continually bombarded with messages that mirror modern-day political arguments on Twitter (as well as obvious references to Trump and Farage, comparing them - of course - to Hitler). The game doesn't *let* you be political neutral, it doesn't *let* you escape the mire of politics, which you would think is one of the reasons you are playing a game in the first place. As a conservative, these aspects significantly broke immersion for me, and made it difficult to get through the game.The second major problem is that the ratio of gameplay vs. movie content is quite poor. Of the 20-ish hours you will spend watching the plot unfold, you will actually not do that much puzzling, acting and deciding. Most of the time you will either be watching cutscenes, or roam through an expansive landscape on your way to the next fetch quest. It's boring. Even the tasks themselves are boring. You spend a good chunk (time-wise) of the introductory part in Stark going to a job and to therapy. Why would I want to do that in a game? I get enough of this sort of ""adventure"" in real life.There are other secondary problems with the gameplay and characters that add up to a disappointing experience overall. It's not a completely terrible game, but it certainly isn't worth the price tag and it does not live up to the legacy of the now 17-year-old original."
