,Recommended,237850,16090917,"Posted: 30 May, 2015",all,Elysium,"Like previous games in the series, Chapters has a compelling story, diverse and intriguing characters.. Beautiful environments.I strongly recommend this entire series to anyone who's ever been lost in their life, as it deals a lot with perspective and how you choose to view the world around you."
,Recommended,237850,16087959,"Posted: 30 May, 2015",all,Sidea,"I have waited years and years for this game. I am a huge fan of the Longest Journey and Dreamfall. They both hold special places in my heart, and I fell in love with April Ryan, Crow, Zoe, and even Kian. The story that is told between both games, even though Dreamfall is not exactly a sequel, is my favorite story I've ever played through in any game. And I've played a lot of games. Yes, I was highly anticipating Dreamfall Chapters.So far only two books have been released, but I'm totally enchanted. The problem is, my enchantment gets suspended for a little too long between books. If you're an impatient fan like me, you should buy the season pass and play as each book gets released. If you're patient, I highly recommend waiting to play the game until it's complete. The time between books really ruins the flow, as both books have ended on cliff hangers that leave you craving more... and then so much time passes that you start to forget about the sense of urgency that you were left with.The story:10/10! It starts out very slow. If you played Dreamfall, this won't be a problem because you'll understand the bigger picture and know why the slow parts of the story are important. If you haven't played Dreamfall, you might think the story is too thin and confusing for a while. So go play Dreamfall first. Dreamfall Chapters is wonderful, because it picks up right where Dreamfall left of: with Zoe's coma. We get to know a lot more about Zoe in the first book. In the second book, we get to know a lot more about the world she's living in in Stark - it's complicated, detailed, and intriguing. We also spend a lot of time with Kian in Arcadia, which is turning into less of a fairy tale place as the story progresses. The story with Arcadia is big, haunting, rich, and still building. I really want to know more!The gameplay:WAY better than in Dreamfall. So far there's no combat, just puzzles and progressing the rich story. It's smooth.The graphics:The game looks great. It may not blow you away with incredible detail that requires two video cards and an overclocked i7 CPU, but it looks very good on any decent middle power computerr. It's clean, has a beautiful artistic style, and you will get sucked into the story because of both the graphics and the great story telling.The puzzles:Overall they're good. There's a couple that felt weak, tedious, or just too long. I've not disliked any of them yet. The game is mostly story so far, but the puzzles blend right into the story and progress it well.The Choice and Consequence system:It's haunting. Did I choose the right choices!? When you get hit with needing to make a choice, you'll find that it's actually really hard. You really have to think through what kind of story experience you want. Should you let that character die for the sins he or she did, or do you think it's worth saving the character because that character might be useful? Should you disobey orders to do something better, or is disobeying too risky? You just have to chose an option and hope for the best. Yes, I will be replaying the game in order to choose the others choices, because I want to see how the story is affected!Conclusion:Go play The Longest Journey and Dreamfall. Your life will be better for it. Then buy this game and play it! Even if you're not an adventure game fan, you can't deny that this series has an amazing story and characters. You're missing out by not getting to know these characters."
