,Recommended,237850,21856071,"Posted: 15 March, 2016",all,dj_moyer,"Did you play ""The Longest Journey"" yet?DId you then play ""Dreamfall: The Longest Journey?""If not, go play those two games first or the story won't make much sense to you.If you played those two games and did not like them, well then you should stay away from this one because it is a sequel.This game picks up a little while after the end of ""Dreamfall: The Longest Journey"" which I will not spoil for those who haven't played it.  Let's just say it was a surprise to me when I played it.  You are still tasked with saving the world (or two worlds, depending how you look at it) and someone is still using people's dreams for evil purposes.  But in this game, you get to make choices along the way that change the way the story plays out.  There are several branching paths you might follow, but each choice is permanent!  Some changes are small, others have big impacts on the events around you.  It is a little bit like a ""choose your own adventure"" story in that sense.Bottom line:this game is a bit different from its predecessors.  In some ways it is better, in other ways I personally prefer one of the other two in teh series.  Do you like adventure games?  Do you like some suspense - rarely knowing how your choices will play out in the long run?  Do you like solving puzzles with seemingly random (and sometimes borderline insane) item combinations?  Do you want to be a super-hero who can walk in and out of other people's dreams?  If you said yes to those questions AND you enjoyed the first two games in this series, then you need to play this game.  I'm not sure what they're charging for it these days but I got it on sale.  Totally worth $15 or $20 I think."
