76561198030249805,Recommended,237850,27979153,"Posted: 28 November, 2016",all,Pentasphere,"Part of a trilogy of games starting with The Longest Journey. The roots of this game is in the more traditional point and click adventure games, although for this one the format has been modernized a bit. If you want to play a game with an amazing, engaging story then this is it. Unlike its two predecessors with a static, fixed story (that were both great!) this game follows the more current trend of allowing you to make decisions that change the story based on what you choose. There are some parts of the game where the pacing can seem a little slow, but overall the narrative (and the choices you can make to change it along the way) keep you invested right until the end. The ability to change the story with your choices also give this game much more replay value than more traditional adventure games of the past. I definitely recommend this game."
,Recommended,237850,28003933,"Posted: 28 November, 2016",all,Captain Serious,"I've always enjoyed point n click adventure games of old.  The classic Lucas Arts and Sierra ""Quest"" games are great examples of the best in the genre.  These classics we're the inspiration for the future games like The Longest Journey (TLJ), which is my all time personal favorite of the genre.Dreamfall Chapters is the 3rd game in the saga, and as of now the conclusion to the series.  There are rumors about a 4th game, but unfortunately it appears our time in Arcadia & Stark and places in between have come to it end.  This saddens me because these worlds, characters, and stories they tell are so beautiful told I'm always left wanting more at the end.However, if there isn't another TLJ game in our future this episodic conclusion to the franchise is a beautiful swansong.  While it leaves a few questions unanswered for potential sequel opportunities, it suffices to bring closure to major plotlines introduced in the 2nd game of the franchise.Let's hope they try another kickstarter for a 4th game.  I'm not ready to leave these worlds behind to memories.  I want to revisit them in the future and see what our familiar friends are up to.We can dream for a continuation of this story, and if it's one thing this game has taught us it's... dreams can change the world."
76561198033659288,Recommended,237850,28022119,"Posted: 28 November, 2016",all,damian.rivas,"I've got to know Dreamfall Chapters because I had interest in playing The Longest Journey adventure game, so I got it and its sequels (Dreamfall: TLJ and Chapters) as well during a Steam's sale.The game follows up the events of Dreamfall: TLJ, expanding Zöe Castillo's  and Kian Alvane's stories, divided into 5 books (episodes), leading to a invevitable conclusion of the TLJ saga as a whole.Chapters mantains a similar gameplay style as its immediate predecessor (Dreamfall: TLJ) but with significant improvements (no more awful fighting engines) while adopting the modern interactive episodic adventure style. In this aspect, what the game offers is not new at all: make decisions which might or might not affect your way forward and lead to different conclusions. As all this kind of games, they focus strength on the plot, the setting and how both develop during gameplay.I liked the game but I would recommed it mostly to people who have played previous installments on the TLJ saga as it seats solidly on its backgroud story. If you are a modern episodic adventure game fan, I'm sure you will enjoy it as well, but not certainly in the same way if you've followed the complete story, or at least played the previous Dreamfall game.For those of you expecting to get a closure or explanation of events on The Longest Journey and Dreamfall: TLJ games, Chapters will give you what you want and well delivered, in my opinion."
