,Not Recommended,237850,19832526,"Posted: 21 December, 2015",all,wobbling,"Short Version:If you still need closure from Dreamfall: The Longest Journey, buy this game on sale but don't expect much in the way of gameplay. If you've never played Dreamfall or the original Longest Journey, play them first. Chapters won't make much sense without them.Longer Version:I loved the first two games, but I'm so very disappointed in Chapters.Everything I loved about the first two games feels like it's missing. The characters are bland, the puzzles are a joke and practically nonexistent, the environments feel strangely empty, the dialogue is sooo awkward (seemed quirky/funny at first, but now just annoying), and the story has become dull and lost all momentum.There is finally a bit of closure for Dreamfall fans out there at the end of Book 5, but it doesn't even come close to making up for the rest of this mess of a game."
76561198006224765,Not Recommended,237850,20096371,"Posted: 29 December, 2015",all,lachs0r,"Gameplay-wise, it’s a point-and-click interactive movie thing with shallow and predictable characters. Think 3D visual novel, complete with writing that would only appeal to 13-year-olds, but without the frustrating story flags that end up killing you and all your loved ones because you made the wrong choice somewhere back in the second chapter. There are very few ways to really screw up in this game. It has very few puzzles (if you could call them that), and they mostly consist of finding and combining items or putting things in the right order. On the positive side, it still manages to make me curious about how things are going to play out, and there’s a little value in replaying the game to see how your choices influence what happens to individual characters (they generally make no difference in the grand scheme of things). The voice acting is quite good.I give it a 3.5/5 there. Entertaining, but far from a masterpiece.Where things really start to crumble though is the technical side. I’m not going to beat around the bush here, this thing’s a MESS and it tends to absolutely ruin the immersion. Graphically, the game looks comparable to titles released in 2006, only with slightly higher texture resolution, a lot of post processing, awful lighting, beginner mistakes (depth/alpha testing failure and z-fighting for instance), distance popping, broken shaders, and rigid, almost robotic character animations that are not timed or positioned correctly most of the time. But it needs a very high-end CPU and gigabytes of RAM to pull this off at acceptable framerates. And even if you have lots of RAM, at some point (roughly 4 GB), performance just falls off a cliff as the garbage collector struggles to deal with all the memory fragmentation because someone thought they didn’t have to care about memory management with a game written using .NET. Nothing could be further from the truth. This seems to happen with a lot of Unity-based titles, so future gamedevs take note—GC’d languages are not a silver bullet. VSync is dysfunctional (probably due the unstable framerate; didn’t attempt to pin down the cause), mouse grabbing does not work properly (cursor leaves the window if you move it too quickly). The list goes on and on. In two hours of gameplay, I hit the “Report Bug” button about a dozen times (as of version 4.1.1). It’s frustrating, to say the least.I still give it 2/5 points here because at least it hasn’t crashed so far, so it’s not totally unplayable.Overall, I don’t think I can recommend this game as it is. I might have reconsidered if the developers had fixed some of the major technical flaws (instead of just the symptoms, like Propast completely wrecking performance in earlier versions), but apparently that is either not very high up on their list of priorities, or they simply lack the expertise to do so."
76561198030717099,Not Recommended,237850,29910987,Posted: 13 February,all,lyre,"Very clumpsy game.It's comfy and neat, with lots of warm memories connected with previous games in this Longest Journey series. It's an ending of the story, and the ending itself is a decent one.However, now I realize, how many cons every game had. From absurd puzzles from the first game (admit, many of us loved that game mostly for story and the world but probably less for gameplay itself); boring fighting system, long runs from one location to another, too simplistic stealth and cliffhanger in the end of the second one; to mostly meaningless choices, mostly too easy or sometimes too hard-to-spot puzzles, and even longer runs from one location to other of this last one installation.Ok, gameplay wasn't the best part of all the series, but the world and dialogues... Nah, dialogues are cheasy and very fanservise-oriented in Dreamfall Chapters. Characters are often dull. And dialogue camera is made with super lazy approach.Unique world - thats the best part here.If you were here before in previous games of this series, then you're already into here.If not - well, think twice.If I were me from the future talking to me from the past, I'd advise me not to play Dreamfall Chapters - better watch letsplays or smth. But I probably wouldn't listen :)"
,Not Recommended,237850,20633741,"Posted: 19 January, 2016",all,Warp,"It is a shame that Steam only offers a binary choice for recommending a game, which means that it's not possible to distinguish between ""a bit on the boring side"" and ""completely unplayable trash"". This game is more on that former side. On a scale from 0 to 10 (where 0 is absolutely horrendous unplayable utterly broken, and 10 is one of the best and most enjoyable games I have played in my life), I would give this a 4. Because it falls just a bit under that ""completely average"" line, I have to give it a negative vote.The major problem I have with this game is that the tasks and puzzles are simplistic, even trivial, and completely unimaginative and outright lazy. It's like no effort whatsoever was put into them, and they were slapped onto the game with no thought or inspiration or effort put into them.What is worse, it seems that no playtesting whatsoever was done on some of the puzzles because, while trivial and unimaginative, some of them can still make you run around for an hour and just not find what you are looking for, for the simple reason that the game literally gives you zero hints of where you have to go or what you have to do. For example, one of the tasks is finding an NPC who is normally at a vending cart, but is not there anymore. No hints whatsoever are given where exactly you should be looking. You can run around the city for hours, looking in every single corner and every single place, and the NPC will be nowhere to be found. Then you look at an online guide and it turns out that you had to check a box behind the vending cart, which contains some receipt, and by taking the receipt that NPC suddenly appears at a location somewhere else in the city... a location you probably checked three times already. The NPC now just magically appears there after you take the receipt. That box is inconspicuous, and unless you happen to stumble across it by chance, chances are that you are going to miss it and waste hours in a wild goose chase. And the ""solution"" is completely nonsensical. (It may have a semblance of sense in terms of storytelling, but as a puzzle it's nonsensical, trivial, needlessly hard with no actual rewarding challenge, and just bad. It's simply a question of whether you happen to check that one box or not.)And that's just one example.The story is also trying really hard to be deep and immersive, but ends up being quite shallow, slow-paced (which isn't helped by the wild goose chase ""puzzles"" you have to ""solve"") and a bit boring.At points I was tempted to just stop playing the game altogether (especially on that ""puzzle"" I described above). I don't find this game all that interesting. The story advances too slowly, and the ""puzzles"" are too trivial, lazy and uninteresting. There is no thought put into them at all.That being said, it's not a horrible game. That's why I'm giving it a 4 out of 10, rather than somehing less."
