,Not Recommended,237850,13766639,"Posted: 1 January, 2015",all,von,"This is a partial review written after finishing ""Book One"". I sincerely hope my verdict will change after the remaining episodes have released, but I currently cannot recommend this game...I have been looking forward to this for quite some time but the experience this far has disappointed me. There is little to no gameplay present save for the conversation wheel and navigating yourself through the city of Europolis. Sure, the game is focused on story and having multiple choices that may(?) change the world around you, but I feel that all the consequences are not clear enough yet. After these first 6 hours of gameplay I have yet to see more than one obvious consequence for an action I have taken. If there are any more actual twists present, they are not clear enough to be noticeable from a single play though.Additionally, I have played both of the previous games, but I feel left out on details from the past story as I can't remember them. The recap that is present is more like a trailer and doesn't really help me remember any details outside of the main plot of the previous game (Dreamfall). The original title - The Longest Journey - is not even mentioned. I can only hope this was a ""prologue"" episode and that the rest of the story will leave enough clues for us ""vets"" to remember exactly where they left us after Dreamfall.I will be waiting for the remaining episodes and update this review in the future.== Update ===It took me two years to get me to pick up this game again and finish it. Sadly, I still can't recommend it fully.The game brings beautiful graphics and art and the story does catch you from time to time, but it's riddled with clichés and bad sex jokes (just, why?) that kinda puts you off after a while. While the characters are likable there are basically three personality types: ""the bland NPC"", ""the bubbly and awkward girl/boy"", ""the angry and bossy man/woman"".However, regardless of the various drawbacks of the story I could see myself enjoying the game if it wasn't for its complete lack of (insteresting) gameplay. The so called puzzles are usually a hide and seek game through a level, and you're sometimes not even told what you are supposed to look for. I never felt I got to crack any actual puzzles. It was more like a mindless wandering and poking everything in my way.Any ""gameplay"" outside of the puzzles and conversations are poorly demonstrated and, dare I say it, completely pointless. At one time you're even placed in a rowing boat on a rail, forced to do nothing but click the left mose button for minutes for no other reason than to progress though the game.CONCLUSION:If you're only here to know what happens in the story of 'Dreamfall' and 'The Longest Journey' and don't care about gameplay at all, go ahead and play it. But if you in any way are an avid puzzle game player, like character development and deep storylines (like 'Mass Effect' or 'Dragon Age') or if you like any kind of gameplay overall; Stay away, this game is not for you."
