76561198031208547,Not Recommended,237850,17447803,"Posted: 8 August, 2015",all,buttwife,"It's an Adventure game in the classic tradition; heavy on the story, light on the gameplay, point and click. It's got all that and for a while it's actually pretty interesting. However, there aren't really any puzzles in the game, it's more errand running to move the story along - which is fine if you like the ambiance.One problem is the way developers sought to slow players progression. Repeatedly, the game will tell you a general goal (""get into X"" or ""find a Y"") and then nothing. Only 30 minutes later (or after checking a FAQ) do you find that the innocuous flavor NPC on a side street ACTUALLY has a new interaction that, when used in the right place, allows you to progress. Nothing will hint that this, you're just expected to click everything again to find it.What got me to uninstall this game though was the hamfisted moral choice-consequence system. Spoilers -- but there's a segment where you're given a choice to Torture or Blackmail a person. Despite the illusion of choice; TORTURE is considered CORRECT. If you don't torture a certain NPC, people will die and then blame you. They will then explain to you how torture is more reliable than blackmail / interrogation. (screenshot:http://nitecrew.biz/images/2015-08-08_00001.jpg)I don't care if there's supposed to be some long-haul lesson about complex morality; torture is always wrong and I can't recommend any media that argues otherwise."
