76561198093145458,Recommended,237850,17230393,"Posted: 25 July, 2015",all,BigBlueDinosaur,"A (mostly) fantastic follow-on to Dreamfall.  Plays similarly to Dreamfall if you omitted the stealth and fight sequences.  I can't say I miss them... usually.  There are ""bits"" of stealth and action, but they are very much bits and don't result in a lot of ""do-overs"".  This game is more about choices, much like a choose-your-own adventure book.  It seems there are many different mays to reach your goals as you play.  There is some puzzle-solving, but most of it is fairly simple... but it *can* occasionally be obtuse and difficult to figure out what to do or even where to start, a bit of a holdover from old point-and-click PC ""adventure"" games of the 80's and 90's I could do without.  (No, I never was able to finish the original ""Longest Journey"", try as I might, obtuse click-puzzles bore me to death.)With months between episodes, I wish there was a ""last time on Dreamfall Chapters"" function that recaps more than just the previous games.  It would also be nice if it were better optimized.  Graphics are nice with great lighting and atmosphere, but there's usually not a lot going on and the character rigs aren't as complex as AAA games.  Seems like it should perform better than 30-50 fps on an i5/R9 380 rig at 1080p.  That said, the fact this thing is made by a very tiny team is impressive.  You can also play it completely with a controller just like the previous game, which to me is a huge plus.I will finally say I just finished episode 3.  I hope all the loose ends get tied up and everything makes sense in a satisfying conclusion.  Unfortunately, I feel like this game has the potential to pull a ""Lost"" or ""Fringe""... just a feeling I have... we shall see.  After all, there's still bits from the original Dreamfall that don't quite fit.I give it 8/10."
